## Building Infinite Scroll in React

**Mental model:** Render a list plus a *sentinel* element at the bottom. An `IntersectionObserver` watches the sentinel; when it scrolls into view, load the next page and append. This beats scroll-event math — the browser tells you exactly when the bottom is near.

### Step 1 — Page state + loading guard
```jsx
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
const [page, setPage] = useState(0);
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
const [done, setDone] = useState(false);
```

### Step 2 — Load + append a page
Guard against concurrent loads and stop when exhausted.

```jsx
const loadMore = useCallback(async () => {
  if (loading || done) return;
  setLoading(true);
  const next = await fetchPage(page);
  setItems((prev) => [...prev, ...next.items]);
  setDone(!next.hasMore);
  setPage((p) => p + 1);
  setLoading(false);
}, [page, loading, done]);
```

### Step 3 — Observe the sentinel
Attach an observer to the sentinel ref; disconnect on cleanup.

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const io = new IntersectionObserver((e) => { if (e[0].isIntersecting) loadMore(); });
  if (sentinel.current) io.observe(sentinel.current);
  return () => io.disconnect();
}, [loadMore]);
```

### Step 4 — Render list + sentinel
```jsx
<>{items.map(renderRow)}<div ref={sentinel} />{loading && <Spinner />}</>
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Double fire | `loading` guard prevents overlapping fetches. |
| End of data | `done` stops further loads (and you can unobserve). |
| Re-create observer | Effect re-runs when `loadMore` identity changes. |

**Interview tip:** Prefer `IntersectionObserver` over a throttled `scroll` listener — it's more efficient and reads cleaner; mention the `loading`/`done` guards that stop duplicate or past-the-end fetches.

