## Building Infinite Scroll in Vue 3

**Mental model:** Render the list plus a *sentinel* at the bottom. An `IntersectionObserver` watches the sentinel; when it enters view, load and append the next page. Far cleaner than scroll-position math.

### Step 1 — Page state + guards
```vue
<script setup>
import { ref } from 'vue';
const items = ref([]);
const page = ref(0);
const loading = ref(false);
const done = ref(false);
</script>
```

### Step 2 — Load + append
```js
async function loadMore() {
  if (loading.value || done.value) return;
  loading.value = true;
  const next = await fetchPage(page.value);
  items.value.push(...next.items);
  done.value = !next.hasMore;
  page.value++;
  loading.value = false;
}
```

### Step 3 — Observe the sentinel via template ref
```js
const sentinel = ref(null);
onMounted(() => {
  io = new IntersectionObserver((e) => { if (e[0].isIntersecting) loadMore(); });
  io.observe(sentinel.value);
});
onUnmounted(() => io.disconnect());
```

### Step 4 — Render list + sentinel
```vue
<li v-for="n in items" :key="n">Item #{{ n }}</li>
<div ref="sentinel" />
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Double fire | `loading` guard prevents overlap. |
| End of data | `done` stops further loads. |
| Cleanup | `io.disconnect()` in `onUnmounted`. |

**Interview tip:** A template `ref` on the sentinel + `IntersectionObserver` set up in `onMounted` (and disconnected in `onUnmounted`) is the idiomatic Vue approach — note that you observe the DOM node only after mount.

