## Building Infinite Scroll in Angular

**Mental model:** Render the list plus a *sentinel* element at the bottom, referenced with `@ViewChild`. An `IntersectionObserver` watches it; when it enters view, load and append the next page. Cleaner than scroll math. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Page state + guards
```typescript
items: number[] = [];
page = 0;
loading = false;
done = false;
@ViewChild('sentinel') sentinel!: ElementRef<HTMLElement>;
```

### Step 2 — Load + append
```typescript
async loadMore(): Promise<void> {
  if (this.loading || this.done) { return; }
  this.loading = true;
  const next = await this.fetchPage(this.page);
  this.items = [...this.items, ...next.items];
  this.done = !next.hasMore;
  this.page++;
  this.loading = false;
}
```

### Step 3 — Observe after view init
```typescript
ngAfterViewInit(): void {
  this.io = new IntersectionObserver((e) => { if (e[0].isIntersecting) { this.loadMore(); } });
  this.io.observe(this.sentinel.nativeElement);
}
ngOnDestroy(): void { if (this.io) { this.io.disconnect(); } }
```

### Step 4 — Render list + sentinel
```html
<li *ngFor="let n of items">Item #{{ n }}</li>
<div #sentinel style="height: 1px"></div>
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Double fire | `loading` guard prevents overlap. |
| End of data | `done` stops further loads. |
| Cleanup | `disconnect()` in `ngOnDestroy`. |

**Interview tip:** Observe the sentinel in `ngAfterViewInit` (the `@ViewChild` DOM node only exists then) and disconnect in `ngOnDestroy` — getting those two lifecycle hooks right is the crux.

